{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4997].
  {panel}

Switching workflows in a fairly large JIRA instance (10000) takes about 90 minutes on a 3Ghz box, with all issues cached and little disk activity.  We should do some profiling and find out why it takes so long.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4989].
  {panel}

It would occasionally be useful if one could have a different default assignee by issue type, in addition to by component.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4972].
  {panel}

It would be nice to have a workflow 'validator' that ensures that transitions are not made with an empty comment.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4961].
  {panel}

Importing larger database can take a long time, especially given that Jira completely rebuilds the search index during the import. This causes browser timeout when loading the page and hence the administrator importing the DB doesn't know if there was a problem without checking the logs or strangely trying to access the site as a regular user and getting an error report of how many percent of the import has been completed.

Confluence has a nice progress bar when reindexing the database, could the same page be implemented for Jira's DB import and reindexing?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4925].
  {panel}

Is it possible to use the attach file field as a custom field? Or is there a plugin available? If not, I think it should be a good new feature to implement.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4916].
  {panel}

Now that gadgets and reports are both implemented as plugins, it should be possible to make them interchangeable, differing in just which view is used to render them.  This would allow users to put any of the reports (popular issues, timetracking, workload, roadmap, changelog) to be placed on the dashboard.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4913].
  {panel}

In larger JIRA installations people use many fields, which requires a lot of scrolling in the create and edit forms.  We should allow fields to be positioned next to one another in field layout schemes, to preserve screen space and improve the look of pages.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4906].
  {panel}

People want to be able to display certain field names and values differently (eg. bolder). 

We should associate a CSS id with field names and values, so users can override the formatting by editing the CSS.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4871].
  {panel}

Presently, sub-tasks viewed in the parent issue can be ordered individually.

Would be useful to add ability to order the sub-tasks by assignee, sub-task type, status, etc.?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4864].
  {panel}

Parent issue should show total voters and watchers for issue AND all sub-tasks.

It would be useful if the voter and watcher list highlighted which sub-task the voter/watcher was interested in also.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4800].
  {panel}

Currently JIRA's encoding (file.encoding system property) is set globally. This means that no matter what language a user picks in their profile preferences, that translation will be served in the default encoding, which may not be able to represent the chosen language.

We need to either store encoding along with locale in the user's preference, or else move to UTF-8 everywhere (there must be _some_ point to unicode).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4794].
  {panel}

Some types of issues (eg "Support Requests") should be private by default.  For this, we need to set the default security level by issue type.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4699].
  {panel}

It would be extremly useful to have POP3-Authentification before sending JIRA-mails, so it is possible to send Emails over Mailserver
without having SMTP_Authentification.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4693].
  {panel}

It would be useful to have a custom field that recorded the number of times that an issue has been in a certain state.  For instance, one could tell how many times an issue has been reopened.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4679].
  {panel}

I would like the ability to give the permission to set a fix version separate from the permission to resolve.
That way a projectleader can schedule issues for a particular version, without having the ability to resolve them.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4665].
  {panel}

Currently, the Mail queue items dont survive an application restart.

The mail queue service recently got stuck with close to 1000 mails in it. (Not sure why - but something to do with our smtp server going down a week ago - the oldest mail queue items matched the smtp server crash date)

In order to rectify it, we had to restart the server - but in doing so we lost all the mails... grr!

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4663].
  {panel}

In the "Developer Workload Report", a developer is shown assigned to 4 issues. After clicking on his username link or on the number of issues link, he is shown assigned to 10 issues. 

It seems that only issues with a time estimate are listed in the Developer Workload Report.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4655].
  {panel}

It would be useful to have a workflow condition that passed if the current issue has a certain priority, or a priority above a certain level.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4646].
  {panel}

It is not possible to set a date to version from which on no more issues can be added to this version.
Better would be a 2 step workflow. After the first "planning end date" only issues with priority Critical or Blocker can be added. After the second deadline only Blocker-Issues can be added.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4641].
  {panel}

Users must perform a reindex after changing Custom Field Searcher types.

This is quite a hassle and might not actually get done anyway. Should be made automatic

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4629].
  {panel}

Currently in JIRA, the 'summary' column claims 100% of available space.  This is fine, except when you have another textarea field like 'description', which needs as much if not more space.  We should work out a more sophisticated means of allocating column widths.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4577].
  {panel}

I would like to have some control over new issues when they are entered - i.e. specify permissions required, specify validation and post-create actions. To be more concrete I would like to fill some internal fields and assign issue in my custom plugin.

The nice point to implement this function is "initial" transition i.e. transition to "New" state.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4569].
  {panel}

Some customers need to be able to view the unique issue id, rather than the issue key - we should display this on the view issue page

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4545].
  {panel}

For certain industries there is a need to provide robust logging of who performed an activity and the current JIRA model of a single login per session does not suffice.  Is there any plans to development the security further such that credentials can be requested at some points in the workflow?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4529].
  {panel}

currently, release notes and other reports URL use version id.

when using maven or other build engines, we'd like to generate a report including the jira report URL, with version name, since only jira knows about version id.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4521].
  {panel}

We found out by surprise that the assignee of an issue created by CreateIssueHandler is the first valid user in the recipient list. I would like to be able to set a parameter (assignee=xxx) that defines who all issues are assigned to, everytime, regardless of who is on the recipient list. This parameter should take either a valid user name, or "defaultassignee" for the default assignee for the project. For now, I have to educate everyone to be careful with who they put first in the recipient list.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4517].
  {panel}

Any possiblity of getting multipart notification emails? As i use both HTML and Text email viewers.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4515].
  {panel}

Currently in the project Default Assignee options there is "Project Lead" and (if enabled) "Unassigned".  There should be a third option, "Disabled (force selection)", which if chosen, would force the user to choose from the available list of users.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4504].
  {panel}

We would like to have issue types assigned to a project category, so that only specific projects or projects within a specific Project Category have access to an issue type.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4503].
  {panel}

We use a project category to group projects and would like the ability to have a custom field scoped to a project category. This would give us some form of project 'inheritence' that we require when creating many projects

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4440].
  {panel}

If JIRA notification mails had a X-JIRA-IssueID header containing the issue ID, one could then rig mail clients with shortcuts to perform operations on issues, most notably 'delete'.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4430].
  {panel}

Currently only the Lead of a project or component gets an email on creating new issues. It is not possible to add other persons, so that they too get emails.

It would be great if a project or a component could have watchers similar to single issues.

Another idea is to let the user mark one of his filters, after each issue is created the issue is run through all marked filters, if a filter matches an email report is sent. This would be even more powerful than a "watch project" feature and it would also automatically take of permissions.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4376].
  {panel}

The date field entry format is currently hardcoded to tt-MMM-yyyy. It would be very useful if other formats can be defined, such as tt.MM.yyyy (used in Germany), of if the format can even be defined in the personal config page.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4361].
  {panel}

Oracle has the infamous problem of not being able to store more than 4000 characters in a VARCHAR2 text field.  JIRA 3 stores edited workflows in a VARCHAR2 field, meaning one cannot copy and edit most workflows when using JIRA with Oracle.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4312].
  {panel}

It would be nice to have multiple timetracking fields that can be used.  Specifically, on our projects we like to have a Team Lead Estimate field that is used for leads to give an estimate of the amount of work required for a given issue.  This value is used (in an XP fashion) to develop a velocity for Team Lead estimates, and thereby predict the amount of work that can be put into a release.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4304].
  {panel}

Sometimes as part of project management one needs to introduce intermidiate, previously unplanned-for releases, or otherwise perform actions that affect many issues at one time.

The "bulk change" feature is very useful in those circumnstances, but having everyone involved receive an e-mail notification per issue changed is NOT helpfult.

Please make bulk changes send a single e-mail notification that starts with information saying that a bulk change was performed.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4302].
  {panel}

When two issues are linked, it would be useful if some fields on the issue were propagated to the linked issue.

For example, imagine you have a user who reports an issue and is watching his email notifications to see how things are going progressing with the bug (and perhaps there are a few other users who are watching the bug as well).  If that issue is then marked as a duplicate, it would be nice if all of those users who were getting notifications for the original bug, started receiving notifications for the new issue as, from their point of view, it is the same issue and they are still interested in it, it just happens to have a different issue ID.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4299].
  {panel}

Users of SSO systems generally also have some sort of external user management.  As a simple first step, JIRA's SSO authenticator could create an OSUser account in JIRA if the SSO authentication succeeds.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4298].
  {panel}

The notification messages table grows quite quickly on large installations of JIRA. Need to create a service that deletes the notification messages after a configurable period of time (or never). After the notification messages are deleted the e-mails will be not be threaded - however, a lot of space could be saved.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4272].
  {panel}

Standalone JIRA should be easily (e.g. with the help of a GUI-frontend) configured to use SSL and/or require client-side certificates. These certificates should be created and managed by JIRA itself (no need to search the internet for documentation about how to do it!). When client-side certificates are active, the user should (optionally) be automatically logged in - no need for a separate user/password login.

This is a must-have feature for us, because we want to connect our JIRA server with the internet, but do not want the world to hack into it.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4254].
  {panel}

In addition to Next 3 Versions and All Versions, we would like to see Released Versions in the road ap.  Or perhaps have All Versions display released versions in the road map.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4233].
  {panel}

Some users often start logging an issue, but then they realise they need to collate more information.

What they would like to do is to be able to save what they have as "Draft" (its not visible to anyone else) and they when they have the full information, they can complete and properly submit it.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4208].
  {panel}

We are using version 2.6.1 enterprise. Would like to know how to define default sort order for issue navigator, or any other views?

Thanks,

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4199].
  {panel}

We have 8 categories and 160 projects in JIRA.
Maybe some categories have more than 50 projects,it will be very difficult to search a project by category.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4184].
  {panel}

It is currently NOT possible to give administration priviledges within the scope of a category, so that such an admin  would be able to create projects within this category but not outside, and would not have to be exposed to ALL the projects?

As a general remark, categories would be extremely useful if they were endowed with more 'namespace-like' feature. This feature request is the most obvious one.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4176].
  {panel}

The main reason why I end up creating additional permission schemes is to allow specific users elevated rights for a particular project.  This is quite a common need, as project leaders often need to delegate certain tasks.  An example is delegation of "defect management" for a project.  Ordinarily, on the assignee, reporter and project lead can edit or re-assign an issue.  However the defect manager needs to be able to do this for any issue in the project. 

Basically what is needed is a built-in per-project group called "Project Admins" or similar.  It would be different for each project (like the project lead is), but could be assigned permissions globally within a scheme.  

Alternatively, you could allow permissions to be assigned to the group of Component Leads (implicitely per-project).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4159].
  {panel}

Currently, JIRA has the browser use HTTP POST to send "find issue" queries to the web server.  This is not as good as could be, since browsers are (correctly) reluctant to do "Reload" on POST transactions.  Better would be to use HTTP GET transactions, which are (by the standard) safe to reload.  This is OK, as issue queries can't change the state of the database.  Then a query page could be re-run by simply hitting Reload.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4118].
  {panel}

We have a number of 'beta' Jelly tags listed on http://www.atlassian.com/software/jira/docs/latest/jelly.html

Eternal beta-ness is not a nice state to be in - we should finish these tags off and document them properly.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4080].
  {panel}

It would be nice to be able to specify a release type (e.g. Alpha, Beta, Production etc).

This change will also enable us to be able to distinguish between defects reported during UAT as apossed to defects in a proudction release.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4077].
  {panel}

The time tracking reports are great except I cannot tell which issues for the selected version do not have time estimates.  It would be nice the time tracking report indicating number of issues without time estimates.  If 0 issues lack time estimates then I can feel pretty comfortable with the information it's giving me, otherwise those issues without time estimates could mean 1 hour or 1 month.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4032].
  {panel}

We have our own script internally, and Arne also sent one (see attachment).

We should document what they do, so that people from non-english languages can translate JIRA easily.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4031].
  {panel}

When users make modification to an issue, issue history should be intelligent and be able to show 'deltas' for all modifications on per-user basis, similar like it shows now changes to status filed.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-4025].
  {panel}

When browsing a group, from the group-browser, when on the list of members of the group, I can click "add User" but this is not an "add user in this group"... why not ? Or shouldn't there be both?

paul

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3994].
  {panel}

The Metal L&F is very, very ugly and tends to look amatuerish.

You can use the default l&f for the client OS - or use jgoodies L&F.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-3989].
  {panel}
